  "prompt": "How much of demonetized money, might not come back to the banking system?",
  "response": "The amount of demonetized money that might not return to the banking system can vary based on several factors, including public trust in the banking system, the effectiveness of the demonetization process, and the socio-economic conditions of the population. \n\nIn the case of India's demonetization in November 2016, where \u20b9500 and \u20b91,000 notes were invalidated, it was estimated that around 99% of the demonetized currency returned to the banking system. However, portions of the currency that were lost due to hoarding, destruction, or because they were held by individuals who were unable or unwilling to exchange them could represent a small percentage that did not come back.\n\nUltimately, the specific percentage of demonetized money that does not return can vary widely based on the context and the measures taken by the government and financial institutions to facilitate the exchange of old currency. Economic analysis and data from central banks after such events can provide insights, but exact figures can be challenging to ascertain.",
